This is not what I think
it means to organize,

00:46:50.476 --> 00:46:53.170
and that is real, and
we should honor that.

00:46:53.170 --> 00:46:56.632
We shouldn't force people to
teach people other things.

00:46:56.632 --> 00:46:58.090
The other thing,
though, is that is

00:46:58.090 --> 00:46:59.600
how some people think
about their work,

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:00.590
and that is also real.

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:03.860
And we should allow
them to do that.

00:47:03.860 --> 00:47:06.845
And I would rather me help
you think through something

00:47:06.845 --> 00:47:10.770
than you like read some crazy
thing from some crazy person,

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:12.520
and then you think
that that is the truth,

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:15.360
and then we're fighting.

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:16.860
So I am one of the
people, like you,

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:18.250
who is like, I think that
we can talk about it.

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:20.660
I don't think that it is
internalized anything,

00:47:20.660 --> 00:47:23.800
but I do think that
we have to always

00:47:23.800 --> 00:47:26.260
be mindful of our
motivations in it.

00:47:26.260 --> 00:47:27.940
There are some people
who are teaching

00:47:27.940 --> 00:47:31.374
because they want the validation
from that crowd, right?

00:47:31.374 --> 00:47:33.790
There are some people who are
teaching to answer questions

00:47:33.790 --> 00:47:37.312
and to be somebody
who helps people think

00:47:37.312 --> 00:47:38.520
about a different experience.

00:47:38.520 --> 00:47:40.422
And I'm somebody who
still is learning

00:47:40.422 --> 00:47:42.380
about the trans community,
for instance, right?

00:47:42.380 --> 00:47:44.430
And if people wouldn't talk
to me about their experience,

00:47:44.430 --> 00:47:45.096
I wouldn't know.

00:47:45.096 --> 00:47:46.805
And I would think I'm
a really good ally,

00:47:46.805 --> 00:47:48.679
and then I say something
crazy, and I'm like,

00:47:48.679 --> 00:47:50.720
well, I tried to ask,
but people-- you know?

00:47:50.720 --> 00:47:53.430
So I'm in that space
of like I need--

00:47:53.430 --> 00:47:57.897
like how do we help
people understand

00:47:57.897 --> 00:47:58.980
this work a little better?

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:00.210
And that doesn't
actually always mean

00:48:00.210 --> 00:48:01.850
that it has to be
a person, right?

00:48:01.850 --> 00:48:05.330
There are some amazing texts
and things like that out there.

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:07.860
But I do think that it is some
people's real work to help

00:48:07.860 --> 00:48:09.700
other people think about
the world a little deeper,

00:48:09.700 --> 00:48:10.600
but it's not everybody's.

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:12.516
I think that, again,
it's like this either/or.

00:48:12.516 --> 00:48:14.730
It's either like nobody's
work or it's everybody's

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:16.210
is how people often paint it.

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:18.210
As opposed to saying,
it might not be yours,

00:48:18.210 --> 00:48:21.280
but it might be mine, which I
think is probably a little more

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:25.030
honest and real, while we make
sure that the people who think

00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:27.410
that this is their work
always check their motivations

00:48:27.410 --> 00:48:28.904
for being in the work.

00:48:28.904 --> 00:48:31.070
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
you're a big fan of Twitter,

00:48:31.070 --> 00:48:34.060
and Twitter has been a great
platform for a lot of people

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:36.129
to sort of be able
to have conversations

00:48:36.129 --> 00:48:37.420
that they couldn't have before.

00:48:37.420 --> 00:48:40.060
At the same time,
Twitter has also

00:48:40.060 --> 00:48:42.850
come up in various
contexts and it

00:48:42.850 --> 00:48:46.350
has an interaction
method that often

00:48:46.350 --> 00:48:47.774
enables harassment and abuse.

00:48:47.774 --> 00:48:49.440
And so I'm wondering
about your thoughts

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:52.980
on navigating the line
between both opening up

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:57.740
conversations but also opening
up vulnerable populations

00:48:57.740 --> 00:48:58.695
in interactions.

00:48:58.695 --> 00:48:59.570
DERAY MCKESSON: Yeah.

00:48:59.570 --> 00:49:01.782
I think it's a good question.

00:49:01.782 --> 00:49:04.240
You know, I've blocked 19,000
people personally on Twitter.

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:05.698
So I completely
get the harassment.

00:49:05.698 --> 00:49:07.072
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:08.965 --> 00:49:10.090
SPEAKER: Like individually?

00:49:10.090 --> 00:49:11.298
DERAY MCKESSON: Individually.

00:49:11.298 --> 00:49:12.136
One at a time.

00:49:12.136 --> 00:49:18.670
And I did a screening of
the Panthers documentary

00:49:18.670 --> 00:49:22.520
in Baltimore at The Charles,
this independent movie theater.

00:49:22.520 --> 00:49:24.207
And people tweeted
in death threats.

00:49:24.207 --> 00:49:26.290
The police came, they shut
down the movie theater.

00:49:26.290 --> 00:49:27.270
So I get it, right?

00:49:27.270 --> 00:49:28.150
I get their recipes.

00:49:28.150 --> 00:49:29.816
And my Twitter account
got hacked the other day.

00:49:29.816 --> 00:49:31.274
My phones got hacked
the other day.

00:49:31.274 --> 00:49:35.290
Somebody called Verizon
impersonating me,

00:49:35.290 --> 00:49:38.420
got the SIM number
changed, so my phone

00:49:38.420 --> 00:49:40.480
was bricked for a little bit.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:42.490
And then they used
2-Factor to hack

00:49:42.490 --> 00:49:46.380
into my Gmail and
my Twitter account.

00:49:46.380 --> 00:49:48.377
So I get the harassment piece.

00:49:48.377 --> 00:49:49.460
There are a couple things.

00:49:49.460 --> 00:49:52.050
One is I think that Twitter
just recently changed

00:49:52.050 --> 00:49:53.880
the blocking feature.

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:56.500
You know, I know the
people at Twitter well.

00:49:56.500 --> 00:49:59.995
I don't always know why they
make the decisions they do.

00:49:59.995 --> 00:50:02.120
There's no blog post about
this change in blocking,

00:50:02.120 --> 00:50:03.604
but I think it is a real change.

00:50:03.604 --> 00:50:05.770
So when you block people
now, they are very blocked.

00:50:05.770 --> 00:50:07.940
Whereas before, if somebody
blocks you and you block them,

00:50:07.940 --> 00:50:08.850
there were like
these workarounds

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:11.290
that you could still interact
with them, essentially.

00:50:11.290 --> 00:50:13.570
And now that is gone, and I
think that's a real thing.

00:50:13.570 --> 00:50:16.200
The thing that people
talk about the most

00:50:16.200 --> 00:50:18.884
is the sheer volume, right?

00:50:18.884 --> 00:50:21.425
So you'll get people who flood
your-- if somebody targets you

00:50:21.425 --> 00:50:23.591
on Twitter, and then all
of a sudden like 100 people

00:50:23.591 --> 00:50:26.370
are tweeting you, it's a pretty
not fun experience, right?

00:50:26.370 --> 00:50:29.120
I don't know what the
quick solution is for that.

00:50:29.120 --> 00:50:30.096
I don't know.

00:50:30.096 --> 00:50:31.470
As somebody who
gets it, I'll get

00:50:31.470 --> 00:50:36.580
people who will put-- you
know, when I got hacked,

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:40.374
somebody spoofed these fake
DMs about me and Netta.

00:50:40.374 --> 00:50:42.040
And they put them all
over the internet.

00:50:42.040 --> 00:50:44.950
So for two days, my mentions
were like just people

00:50:44.950 --> 00:50:46.020
upset about that.

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:47.564
Because the DMs
are like, you want

00:50:47.564 --> 00:50:49.480
to put martial law in
the country or whatever.

00:50:49.480 --> 00:50:51.010
So literally, it's
like hundreds of like,

00:50:51.010 --> 00:50:52.330
why do you want martial law?

00:50:52.330 --> 00:50:54.460
And I'm like, get
these out of here!

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:56.420
I don't know what
Twitter would have done.

00:50:56.420 --> 00:51:00.820
I don't know what the solution
looks like in that space.

00:51:00.820 --> 00:51:03.360
I do think Twitter is really
slow around the harassment

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:03.880
stuff.

00:51:03.880 --> 00:51:07.497
So you submit a
thing saying you've

00:51:07.497 --> 00:51:09.830
been harassed or whatever,
and it's like 10 hours later.

00:51:09.830 --> 00:51:11.650
And they've got to
figure that out, right?

00:51:11.650 --> 00:51:14.630
There's a volume issue there
I think is tough for them,

00:51:14.630 --> 00:51:17.040
because people abuse
the report function too.

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:20.410
People will mass report somebody
they hate as being hacked,

00:51:20.410 --> 00:51:22.167
and then they'll
freeze their account.

00:51:22.167 --> 00:51:23.750
And they need to
figure that part out.

00:51:23.750 --> 00:51:26.486
I think that they have not
figured out the speed part.

00:51:26.486 --> 00:51:28.110
And when my Twitter
account got hacked,

00:51:28.110 --> 00:51:30.462
it took me a while to get
back in, and I know them.

00:51:30.462 --> 00:51:31.554
Right?

00:51:31.554 --> 00:51:33.220
And the speed piece
I think is like what

00:51:33.220 --> 00:51:36.440
actually-- which is what I worry
about more than anything else.

00:51:36.440 --> 00:51:37.944
I do think it's
unique in the sense

00:51:37.944 --> 00:51:39.610
that it's the most
open platform, right?

00:51:39.610 --> 00:51:40.705
Facebook is your friends.

00:51:40.705 --> 00:51:42.080
So when they say
something crazy,

00:51:42.080 --> 00:51:44.286
you'll unfriend
them or something

00:51:44.286 --> 00:51:46.070
and then maybe block
them or report them,

00:51:46.070 --> 00:51:46.927
but it's different.

00:51:46.927 --> 00:51:48.510
Twitter is like
standing on the corner

00:51:48.510 --> 00:51:50.634
and it's like the world
is right there, right?

00:51:50.634 --> 00:51:52.050
And there's this
question of like,

00:51:52.050 --> 00:51:54.682
do you put up these [? cones ?]
so the world can't see you,

00:51:54.682 --> 00:51:56.140
which fundamentally
changes what it

00:51:56.140 --> 00:51:57.500
means to stand on the corner.

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:00.440
Or do you make sure that
people can't run you over?

00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:02.584
It's like what are the
two pendulant swings?

00:52:02.584 --> 00:52:04.750
And I think that Twitter
is still finding its space.

00:52:04.750 --> 00:52:06.620
But I do think it
doesn't get credit

00:52:06.620 --> 00:52:10.709
for how hard it is to keep the
commitment it has while making

00:52:10.709 --> 00:52:12.000
sure that the platform is safe.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:13.755
I do think that they've been
really slow on user names,

00:52:13.755 --> 00:52:14.470
though.

00:52:14.470 --> 00:52:16.261
You shouldn't be able
to have a name that's

00:52:16.261 --> 00:52:17.280
like I hate the N word.

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:18.620
That doesn't make sense to me.

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:20.236
And they have been
slow on there.

00:52:20.236 --> 00:52:21.860
I have no insider
knowledge about this,

00:52:21.860 --> 00:52:26.060
but I think that they also have
not moved away from the rat

00:52:26.060 --> 00:52:27.240
race around users, right?

00:52:27.240 --> 00:52:29.140
They're in this user
race with Facebook.

00:52:29.140 --> 00:52:31.530
And I think that Twitter's
real story is about impact,

00:52:31.530 --> 00:52:34.015
and they have not figured out
a metric around impact yet.

00:52:34.015 --> 00:52:35.890
And if they did, I think
that they would win.

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:38.930
Like they'd win that fight, but
they are still fighting people

00:52:38.930 --> 00:52:39.900
around this user thing.

00:52:39.900 --> 00:52:41.816
And you think about
yesterday with the sit-in.

00:52:41.816 --> 00:52:45.340
And it's like, when Paul
Ryan cut off C-SPAN,

00:52:45.340 --> 00:52:46.620
it was Periscope.

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:47.400
That was it.

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:49.840
It was an immediate-- like
this is an impact thing.

00:52:49.840 --> 00:52:52.100
And they are still fighting
people in this user thing

00:52:52.100 --> 00:52:53.240
that I think is a loss.

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:55.800
I think they will not
win the user fight.

00:52:55.800 --> 00:52:56.730
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:52:56.730 --> 00:52:58.480
So my question is
about something

00:52:58.480 --> 00:53:00.520
you were talking about
earlier, calling out

00:53:00.520 --> 00:53:02.100
comments that people make.

00:53:02.100 --> 00:53:04.450
This is something I
really want to do more.

00:53:04.450 --> 00:53:08.260
And I think I'm kind of getting
better and better at doing it.

00:53:08.260 --> 00:53:10.260
I think it's a lot
easier though, for me,

00:53:10.260 --> 00:53:11.930
when it's in a context
when, you know,

00:53:11.930 --> 00:53:13.240
I'm talking to
another white person,

00:53:13.240 --> 00:53:14.530
or there are only
white people there.

00:53:14.530 --> 00:53:16.196
Where it's been a lot
more difficult is,

00:53:16.196 --> 00:53:18.830
there are people of
color in the group who

00:53:18.830 --> 00:53:21.992
don't respond to the comment,
or even sometimes seem

00:53:21.992 --> 00:53:22.700
to agree with it.

00:53:22.700 --> 00:53:25.240
And I think where this has
come up for me in particular

00:53:25.240 --> 00:53:28.490
is with older gay men in the
city, which a lot of people

00:53:28.490 --> 00:53:32.130
will know that the gay
community in San Francisco does

00:53:32.130 --> 00:53:33.720
tend to skew older.

00:53:33.720 --> 00:53:36.650
So I've come across
older gay men of color

00:53:36.650 --> 00:53:40.540
who don't seem to want to
respond to these comments.

00:53:40.540 --> 00:53:44.270
And I don't know if it's because
this is like a way of survival,

00:53:44.270 --> 00:53:46.540
having been in this community
for so long, that they

00:53:46.540 --> 00:53:47.717
kind of-- I don't know.

00:53:47.717 --> 00:53:49.800
I guess I'm wondering if
you have noticed anything

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:52.924
like that, if you have
any advice for how

00:53:52.924 --> 00:53:53.965
to address the situation.

00:53:53.965 --> 00:53:54.350
DERAY MCKESSON: Yeah.

00:53:54.350 --> 00:53:56.190
Sometimes it is real that
people-- sometimes people

00:53:56.190 --> 00:53:58.273
stay stuff around me that,
I should say something,

00:53:58.273 --> 00:54:00.165
but I'm like, I'm
too tired today.

00:54:00.165 --> 00:54:01.712
We're going to go
back and forth,

00:54:01.712 --> 00:54:02.920
and I just can't do it today.

00:54:02.920 --> 00:54:05.450
I think about the woman-- and
this woman worked on the Amtrak

00:54:05.450 --> 00:54:05.710
train.

00:54:05.710 --> 00:54:07.250
And she said something
crazy the other day.

00:54:07.250 --> 00:54:08.791
And I just had to
tweet like, I'm not

00:54:08.791 --> 00:54:11.365
going to let the devil get
me, because [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:11.365 --> 00:54:12.220
So that is real.

00:54:12.220 --> 00:54:14.970
So some people are
tired, and that's real.

00:54:14.970 --> 00:54:19.487
Confrontation, though, the
word sounds harsher than it is.

00:54:19.487 --> 00:54:20.820
I think there are simple things.

00:54:20.820 --> 00:54:22.194
Like, "What did
you mean by that"

00:54:22.194 --> 00:54:25.000
is totally a way to start
a conversation with people

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:28.340
that gets you on the
path of either holding

00:54:28.340 --> 00:54:30.770
people accountable or
changing people's minds

00:54:30.770 --> 00:54:33.100
but is a very simple entrance.

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:36.529
And I think with people that
you have seen not address things

00:54:36.529 --> 00:54:38.820
that you think are sort of
problematic, I think there's

00:54:38.820 --> 00:54:41.220
a way to say like, I thought
that was really troubling,

00:54:41.220 --> 00:54:43.260
what did you think about that,
as a way to sort of get to the,

00:54:43.260 --> 00:54:44.250
why didn't you say anything?

00:54:44.250 --> 00:54:45.990
So that you can learn
a little better.

00:54:45.990 --> 00:54:48.610
I do think that
people, unfortunately,

00:54:48.610 --> 00:54:50.660
start to think about
confrontation as this like

00:54:50.660 --> 00:54:53.034
you need to have a billboard
that's like, I can't believe

00:54:53.034 --> 00:54:55.750
you let your community down,
which is a not helpful way

00:54:55.750 --> 00:54:57.345
to think about this work.

00:54:57.345 --> 00:54:58.720
But I think there
are simple ways

00:54:58.720 --> 00:55:02.220
to create the entrance that
then allow you to build,

00:55:02.220 --> 00:55:04.510
which is like, what
made you say that?

00:55:04.510 --> 00:55:07.239
What did you mean by that?

00:55:07.239 --> 00:55:09.030
I think those questions,
I've seen those be

00:55:09.030 --> 00:55:11.040
super effective entry points.

00:55:11.040 --> 00:55:13.510
And then you just need to be
thoughtful about continuing

00:55:13.510 --> 00:55:13.830
that.

00:55:13.830 --> 00:55:15.955
And that puts, again, the
onus on the other person.

00:55:15.955 --> 00:55:17.250
Like you're not doing the work.

00:55:17.250 --> 00:55:18.541
They're doing the hardest work.

00:55:18.541 --> 00:55:20.800
You're doing the work
of asking the question.

00:55:20.800 --> 00:55:24.256
AUDIENCE: I love the policy
proposals and the platform

00:55:24.256 --> 00:55:25.810
on Campaign Zero.

00:55:25.810 --> 00:55:28.980
It looks amazing, and I'm
really interested in seeing

00:55:28.980 --> 00:55:31.940
how it can be brought in
the local and state level

00:55:31.940 --> 00:55:33.110
and national level.

00:55:33.110 --> 00:55:36.100
One thing I'm wondering about,
though-- particularly because

00:55:36.100 --> 00:55:40.990
in San Francisco we've had
a huge increase in property

00:55:40.990 --> 00:55:43.120
crimes recently.

00:55:43.120 --> 00:55:46.940
There have been two stabbings
within a block of my apartment.

00:55:46.940 --> 00:55:51.620
And I know that the
constituency in my neighborhood,

00:55:51.620 --> 00:55:55.560
which is the Castro, which is
generally whiter, wealthier,

00:55:55.560 --> 00:55:59.080
even if gay, would have--
like their instinct would

00:55:59.080 --> 00:56:05.000
be to demand even more
enforcement of these loitering

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.879
laws and those kind of things.

00:56:07.879 --> 00:56:10.170
And then at the same time,
I see from my parents living

00:56:10.170 --> 00:56:13.500
in New Orleans, which has also
been going through a crime

00:56:13.500 --> 00:56:17.610
wave, their instinct is
to have more police that

00:56:17.610 --> 00:56:20.370
are intervening more.

00:56:20.370 --> 00:56:23.380
So I guess what I want to know
is, from your perspective,

00:56:23.380 --> 00:56:27.470
when you're having conversations
with people whose instinct is

00:56:27.470 --> 00:56:31.030
driven by fear, and who
look to the police as a way

00:56:31.030 --> 00:56:33.870
of assuaging that fear, and
you want to say to them,

00:56:33.870 --> 00:56:36.300
hey, no, this is a
longer term solution,

00:56:36.300 --> 00:56:40.950
and we need to actually get here
so that everyone feels safe,

00:56:40.950 --> 00:56:43.302
how do you approach
that and what works?

00:56:43.302 --> 00:56:44.760
DERAY MCKESSON:
People's proclivity

00:56:44.760 --> 00:56:47.020
to call for the police
makes total sense to me.

00:56:47.020 --> 00:56:49.100
In a world where
we have made people

00:56:49.100 --> 00:56:50.970
believe that police
equals safety.

00:56:50.970 --> 00:56:53.830
I get it, whether I
agree with it or not.

00:56:53.830 --> 00:56:56.730
I think that when we think
about community violence--

00:56:56.730 --> 00:56:59.560
if you think about
the legal economy,

00:56:59.560 --> 00:57:01.060
there's a way to
deal with conflict.

00:57:01.060 --> 00:57:02.665
If I don't like you,
I call your boss.

00:57:02.665 --> 00:57:03.619
I file a lawsuit.

00:57:03.619 --> 00:57:04.410
I file a complaint.

00:57:04.410 --> 00:57:05.890
There's a whole apparatus.

00:57:05.890 --> 00:57:07.790
In the illegal economy,
there's only one way

00:57:07.790 --> 00:57:10.070
to deal with conflict,
and there's violence.

00:57:10.070 --> 00:57:13.930
So if the solution to community
violence, all that stuff,

00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:16.710
is not about getting people
out of the illegal economy,

00:57:16.710 --> 00:57:18.480
I think we will always
spin our wheels.

00:57:18.480 --> 00:57:24.160
Any solution that isn't about
like jobs, education, housing,

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:27.620
those are the actual solutions
that will change the needle.

00:57:27.620 --> 00:57:29.810
In the absence of those,
the police, I think,

00:57:29.810 --> 00:57:32.210
will always be
people's best solution.

00:57:32.210 --> 00:57:35.000
So when you think about
Baltimore, 40% of adults

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:36.440
can't functionally read.

00:57:36.440 --> 00:57:37.530
It's a crisis, right?

00:57:37.530 --> 00:57:39.370
So we could bring
every industry we

00:57:39.370 --> 00:57:40.940
want in America to Baltimore.

00:57:40.940 --> 00:57:42.930
People can't read, not
going to matter, right?

00:57:42.930 --> 00:57:45.820
It's going to matter
significantly less.

00:57:45.820 --> 00:57:48.980
People are going to wake up
being like, I need money.

00:57:48.980 --> 00:57:50.690
How do I get it?

00:57:50.690 --> 00:57:53.850
And if that is selling drugs
or doing whatever, people are

00:57:53.850 --> 00:57:55.900
going to get their needs met.

00:57:55.900 --> 00:57:59.790
And again, I think the work
around getting people out

00:57:59.790 --> 00:58:04.379
of the illegal economy is
like the not sexy, super dull

00:58:04.379 --> 00:58:06.670
but like the work that actually
changes people's lives.

00:58:06.670 --> 00:58:07.800
If you think about the
homeless populations,

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:10.570
it's like, we know that it
is better for homeless people

00:58:10.570 --> 00:58:13.140
to be in homes than not,
which sounds really simple.

00:58:13.140 --> 00:58:15.570
But there are people who
will see a homeless person

00:58:15.570 --> 00:58:17.846
and will take them to
drug treatment first.

00:58:17.846 --> 00:58:19.220
And we actually
know the outcomes

00:58:19.220 --> 00:58:21.910
if you do that are worse
than if you actually

00:58:21.910 --> 00:58:23.724
just put the person in a home.

00:58:23.724 --> 00:58:25.557
And it's called the
"housing first" strategy

00:58:25.557 --> 00:58:29.330
that people need homes before
they need anything else.

00:58:29.330 --> 00:58:31.500
But it's easier to be like,
we're going to put you

00:58:31.500 --> 00:58:32.666
in drug treatment for today!

00:58:32.666 --> 00:58:35.720
And then you actually didn't
solve any of the problems.

00:58:35.720 --> 00:58:38.590
So I don't know a great
response to people

00:58:38.590 --> 00:58:40.670
who call the police like
that, because I get it.

00:58:40.670 --> 00:58:42.790
I get why older people
do it specifically,

00:58:42.790 --> 00:58:44.500
my grandmother
being one of them.

00:58:44.500 --> 00:58:46.545
But I also believe
that the way to get out

00:58:46.545 --> 00:58:48.670
of that is to really think
about community violence

00:58:48.670 --> 00:58:52.030
in a completely different way
that is very structural, very

00:58:52.030 --> 00:58:52.880
not sexy.

00:58:52.880 --> 00:58:55.402
It's about jobs,
literacy, access,

00:58:55.402 --> 00:58:57.360
those sort of things,
transportation, you know?

00:58:57.360 --> 00:58:59.214
I know people in
Baltimore who can only

00:58:59.214 --> 00:59:00.880
work in parts of the
city because that's

00:59:00.880 --> 00:59:02.340
where the buses go, right?

00:59:02.340 --> 00:59:05.312
So they physically cannot get
to another part of town in less

00:59:05.312 --> 00:59:07.520
than three hours, and they're
not going to get a job.

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:08.070
They just won't.

00:59:08.070 --> 00:59:10.278
They're not going to make
that choice, which severely

00:59:10.278 --> 00:59:12.950
limits the opportunities they
have, which is a crazy thing.

00:59:12.950 --> 00:59:14.160
That's real, though.

00:59:14.160 --> 00:59:16.080
AUDIENCE: My question
is-- well, first of all,

00:59:16.080 --> 00:59:19.650
we know that change is
not happening fast enough.

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:22.930
And you were talking about sort
of the stages of organizing

00:59:22.930 --> 00:59:25.850
and how only the third
one, the third step,

00:59:25.850 --> 00:59:27.730
is being able to see outcomes.

00:59:27.730 --> 00:59:30.490
And that's obviously
not fast enough

00:59:30.490 --> 00:59:33.260
because people's
lives are on the line.

00:59:33.260 --> 00:59:37.040
And I'm just curious about how
you personally stay patient,

00:59:37.040 --> 00:59:41.130
and how you stay sane, and how
you bear witness and organize

00:59:41.130 --> 00:59:44.390
around all these things when
you put so much effort in

00:59:44.390 --> 00:59:46.637
and things are
still so very slow?

00:59:46.637 --> 00:59:47.470
DERAY MCKESSON: Yep.

00:59:47.470 --> 00:59:50.010
So I know I'm not alone,
and that's important to me,

00:59:50.010 --> 00:59:53.140
that I'm one of many people
who are doing this work.

00:59:53.140 --> 00:59:56.020
I have great friends,
which is helpful.

00:59:56.020 --> 00:59:57.599
And I was a teacher.

00:59:57.599 --> 00:59:59.390
You know, I used to
teach sixth grade math,

00:59:59.390 --> 01:00:01.540
and I feel a
responsibility to make sure

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:03.300
that those kids
live in a world that

01:00:03.300 --> 01:00:05.160
is not the world I grew up in.

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:07.020
And that keeps me
hopeful, you know?

01:00:07.020 --> 01:00:09.937
I'm like, I got
it, we can do it.

01:00:09.937 --> 01:00:12.520
And all across the country, I've
seen people find their voices

01:00:12.520 --> 01:00:15.699
and step up in ways that give me
incredible-- like if I had not

01:00:15.699 --> 01:00:17.240
been in Ferguson,
I think I would not

01:00:17.240 --> 01:00:19.380
be an organizer in
this way right now.

01:00:19.380 --> 01:00:22.380
But I saw all these people who
never, ever would be together.

01:00:22.380 --> 01:00:26.540
Like doctors, lawyers,
unemployed people, [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:26.540 --> 01:00:28.540
We were all of one
community in a way

01:00:28.540 --> 01:00:30.394
that all those other
labels didn't matter.

01:00:30.394 --> 01:00:31.810
We were people
with shared values,

01:00:31.810 --> 01:00:33.920
and that really changed me.

01:00:33.920 --> 01:00:35.630
And that gives me
this immense hope.

01:00:35.630 --> 01:00:37.470
And again it is, I
believe, two things--

01:00:37.470 --> 01:00:38.880
there are more people that want
to do the work than know what

01:00:38.880 --> 01:00:40.310
to do, and more people
that want to good work

01:00:40.310 --> 01:00:41.680
than want to be members.

01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:43.550
And, for me, there's
this huge challenge of,

01:00:43.550 --> 01:00:45.469
how do we organize those people?

01:00:45.469 --> 01:00:46.510
And I think we can do it.

01:00:46.510 --> 01:00:48.400
I think tech will be a
part of how we do it.

01:00:48.400 --> 01:00:50.670
I think we've been trying
to figure out slowly--

01:00:50.670 --> 01:00:52.160
partly because people have
been dealing with the day

01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:53.840
to day trauma, so they
haven't pulled back

01:00:53.840 --> 01:00:55.340
to think about sort
of macro spaces.

01:00:55.340 --> 01:00:57.993
But that keeps me
really hopeful.

01:00:57.993 --> 01:00:58.900
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:00:58.900 --> 01:01:00.959
AUDIENCE: And along
with Andy and many,

01:01:00.959 --> 01:01:03.500
many other medical students who
are part of this organization

01:01:03.500 --> 01:01:05.200
called White Coats
for Black Lives.

01:01:05.200 --> 01:01:08.590
And it focuses on
bringing attention

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:11.960
to structural racism and gun
violence and other issues that

01:01:11.960 --> 01:01:14.140
are public health
issues but historically

01:01:14.140 --> 01:01:15.870
haven't been thought of as so.

01:01:15.870 --> 01:01:21.140
And my question is throughout
my year and a half or so

01:01:21.140 --> 01:01:22.910
being involved with
this, I've come

01:01:22.910 --> 01:01:26.520
across many people whose hearts
and minds are already one.

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:28.950
But because of the structure,
or because of things

01:01:28.950 --> 01:01:30.920
they have on the line,
or because of things

01:01:30.920 --> 01:01:32.295
they don't have
on the line, they

01:01:32.295 --> 01:01:36.101
don't feel motivated
to either effect change

01:01:36.101 --> 01:01:37.100
or to join the movement.

01:01:37.100 --> 01:01:41.710
And so I guess my
question is, how do you

01:01:41.710 --> 01:01:45.760
get people to contribute more
once you've already convinced

01:01:45.760 --> 01:01:47.330
them of what you're doing?

01:01:47.330 --> 01:01:48.580
DERAY MCKESSON: Good question.

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:51.309
I met with the people who
run Doctors for America,

01:01:51.309 --> 01:01:52.850
and I think they're
doing great work,

01:01:52.850 --> 01:01:54.140
and I think y'all
are doing great work.

01:01:54.140 --> 01:01:56.056
With the health care
thing, I think some of it

01:01:56.056 --> 01:01:56.860
is messaging, too.

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:59.640
Like I think we should
talk about healthcare--

01:01:59.640 --> 01:02:01.850
our health beyond hospitals.

01:02:01.850 --> 01:02:04.640
That's a simpler way to
think about it, that health

01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:07.410
is about so much more than
when you go to the doctor,

01:02:07.410 --> 01:02:09.146
that health is a
broader thing, and we

01:02:09.146 --> 01:02:10.770
need a public
conversation, and doctors

01:02:10.770 --> 01:02:12.061
need to lead that conversation.

01:02:12.061 --> 01:02:13.089
So that's one piece.

01:02:13.089 --> 01:02:15.130
What do you do after you've
won hearts and minds?

01:02:15.130 --> 01:02:17.796
Hearts and minds is hard to win,
so that's like you pat yourself

01:02:17.796 --> 01:02:19.270
on the back for two seconds.

01:02:19.270 --> 01:02:23.280
And then I think it's about
being as explicit as possible

01:02:23.280 --> 01:02:25.190
about what the ask is.

01:02:25.190 --> 01:02:27.292
Because I think that
sometimes we figure out,

01:02:27.292 --> 01:02:29.250
we got this community,
we're like, people care.

01:02:29.250 --> 01:02:30.250
And then we're like,
go do the work!

01:02:30.250 --> 01:02:31.300
And people are like,
well what does that mean?

01:02:31.300 --> 01:02:32.425
And they're like, the work.

01:02:32.425 --> 01:02:34.340
And you're like, I
don't really know.

01:02:34.340 --> 01:02:36.173
And I think that that
actually doesn't help.

01:02:36.173 --> 01:02:38.639
I think that's how we lose
people really quickly,

01:02:38.639 --> 01:02:40.680
is that they feel like
it's like a lot of hot air

01:02:40.680 --> 01:02:44.130
when, in reality,
I think that making

01:02:44.130 --> 01:02:46.180
the choice around what
the discrete thing to do

01:02:46.180 --> 01:02:48.860
is actually really hard,
and organizers always

01:02:48.860 --> 01:02:49.950
feel really pained.

01:02:49.950 --> 01:02:52.917
Because there's a million
things that people should do.

01:02:52.917 --> 01:02:54.750
So saying to people
like, here are the three

01:02:54.750 --> 01:02:55.850
things we want you
to do right now

01:02:55.850 --> 01:02:58.340
is something I've seen even
the most incredible organizers

01:02:58.340 --> 01:02:59.600
really shy away from.

01:02:59.600 --> 01:03:01.620
Because they're nervous
that they're forgetting

01:03:01.620 --> 01:03:02.620
something or da, da, da.

01:03:02.620 --> 01:03:05.110
But I think that that is
actually what keeps people.

01:03:05.110 --> 01:03:06.859
Just like when I was
a teacher-- you know,

01:03:06.859 --> 01:03:08.095
kids want to feel success.

01:03:08.095 --> 01:03:09.470
They want to walk
into a building

01:03:09.470 --> 01:03:11.280
and feel successful every day.

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:12.084
And so do adults.

01:03:12.084 --> 01:03:13.500
Adults want to
feel like the thing

01:03:13.500 --> 01:03:17.080
that they devoted their time
to is part of a success story.

01:03:17.080 --> 01:03:18.894
And some of that we
have to be like-- we

01:03:18.894 --> 01:03:20.310
have to be
manufacturing the sense

01:03:20.310 --> 01:03:22.230
that we have to be really
thoughtful about it.

01:03:22.230 --> 01:03:25.130
It's like when I give the
first test in-- when I taught,

01:03:25.130 --> 01:03:27.465
first test, every kid
was going to pass it.

01:03:27.465 --> 01:03:28.840
I wasn't giving
them the answers,

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:31.360
but it was like
just hard enough,

01:03:31.360 --> 01:03:33.070
but we would do enough
prep right before

01:03:33.070 --> 01:03:36.230
that I knew that you had
to sleep through the test

01:03:36.230 --> 01:03:36.730
to fail it.

01:03:36.730 --> 01:03:38.521
Everybody was going to
pass the first test.

01:03:38.521 --> 01:03:39.600
Second test, super hard.

01:03:39.600 --> 01:03:41.350
It was like all this
content that I needed

01:03:41.350 --> 01:03:43.130
them to really, really grasp.

01:03:43.130 --> 01:03:46.090
But I needed to set up a system
where they felt successful

01:03:46.090 --> 01:03:47.600
when the challenges came.

01:03:47.600 --> 01:03:49.190
And I think that
in organizing work,

01:03:49.190 --> 01:03:53.284
we have to make sure that people
can experience success early,

01:03:53.284 --> 01:03:55.200
or they know that they've
experienced success.

01:03:55.200 --> 01:03:58.340
And then we offer things
that they can actually do.

01:03:58.340 --> 01:04:00.625
So even when it might
be a loss, the success

01:04:00.625 --> 01:04:03.000
is like, it's a new community,
and it's a new da, da, da.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:05.370
That we are always thinking
about how we make people

01:04:05.370 --> 01:04:07.000
feel like they're
doing something.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:08.190
Because you know
as well as I know

01:04:08.190 --> 01:04:09.780
there are a million things that
are competing with your time,

01:04:09.780 --> 01:04:10.280
right?

01:04:10.280 --> 01:04:13.700
You could be watching "Game of
Thrones"-- great last episode.

01:04:13.700 --> 01:04:15.240
Or you could be
organizing, right?

01:04:15.240 --> 01:04:16.970
And you want people to choose
the thing that you're doing.

01:04:16.970 --> 01:04:18.803
But I do think it's
about how are you really

01:04:18.803 --> 01:04:21.990
discrete with what the ask is.

01:04:21.990 --> 01:04:23.110
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

01:04:23.110 --> 01:04:24.570
AUDIENCE: I was
interested in you

01:04:24.570 --> 01:04:26.770
were talking about the
issues of homelessness

01:04:26.770 --> 01:04:28.820
and earlier about
the issues dealing

01:04:28.820 --> 01:04:32.260
with the police contracts.

01:04:32.260 --> 01:04:34.940
And I found, in a
lot of cases, it

01:04:34.940 --> 01:04:38.300
looks like theoretically there's
a program to help someone.

01:04:38.300 --> 01:04:40.700
But when you really
dig into it, there's

01:04:40.700 --> 01:04:46.300
so much paperwork and
so much unsexy barriers.

01:04:46.300 --> 01:04:49.540
What can you do as
advocates to try

01:04:49.540 --> 01:04:54.150
to get attention around those
issues and to deal with them?

01:04:54.150 --> 01:04:58.430
Like, my uncle is pretty
much nonfunctional,

01:04:58.430 --> 01:05:01.910
and it took six months
of constant work

01:05:01.910 --> 01:05:05.790
from multiple relatives just
to get him basic Medicaid.

01:05:05.790 --> 01:05:09.410
And they still have
to administer it.

01:05:09.410 --> 01:05:13.940
There's no program to actually
give him the help he needs.

01:05:13.940 --> 01:05:15.140
DERAY MCKESSON: Yeah.

01:05:15.140 --> 01:05:16.950
I mean, I think this is where
tech people come in, too.

01:05:16.950 --> 01:05:18.650
And this is why I
think it's important

01:05:18.650 --> 01:05:20.983
that we do keep talking about
the problems, but not only

01:05:20.983 --> 01:05:23.370
the problems, is that-- I
think that some people who have

01:05:23.370 --> 01:05:25.828
incredible skill that can help
us organize differently just

01:05:25.828 --> 01:05:28.104
don't know what parts
of the world look like.

01:05:28.104 --> 01:05:29.520
And then it's like,
how do we help

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:31.439
people be exposed
to those experiences

01:05:31.439 --> 01:05:32.480
so they can do something?

01:05:32.480 --> 01:05:34.830
Like there's this great Twilio--
I know a lot about Twilio

01:05:34.830 --> 01:05:35.496
all of a sudden.

01:05:35.496 --> 01:05:38.070
But these people have
created this way--

01:05:38.070 --> 01:05:40.700
so food stamps go
unclaimed in communities

01:05:40.700 --> 01:05:41.835
all across the country.

01:05:41.835 --> 01:05:43.210
And one of the
problems is people

01:05:43.210 --> 01:05:44.820
don't want to go sit at the
Social Security building

01:05:44.820 --> 01:05:46.062
and then type in [INAUDIBLE].

01:05:46.062 --> 01:05:47.270
Who wants to do that all day?

01:05:47.270 --> 01:05:49.480
So they've created
a text-based way

01:05:49.480 --> 01:05:51.355
to figure out if you
qualify for food stamps.

01:05:51.355 --> 01:05:52.610
So you text this number.

01:05:52.610 --> 01:05:54.770
You fill out the whole
questionnaire on text.

01:05:54.770 --> 01:05:57.050
It pops out at the end,
like you do qualify or not.

01:05:57.050 --> 01:05:58.591
So by the time you
get to the office,

01:05:58.591 --> 01:06:00.400
you already know,
yes or no, right?

01:06:00.400 --> 01:06:02.000
Fascinating tech solution.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:03.370
Totally simple.

01:06:03.370 --> 01:06:06.416
I don't know anybody who
knows the number, right?

01:06:06.416 --> 01:06:07.540
But it is a great solution.

01:06:07.540 --> 01:06:10.320
And it's like how do we have
people build the solutions

01:06:10.320 --> 01:06:12.100
and then put them out there?

01:06:12.100 --> 01:06:13.850
When I was running for
mayor of Baltimore,

01:06:13.850 --> 01:06:16.390
I did a visit to
Meals On Wheels.

01:06:16.390 --> 01:06:18.420
Did you know the average
age of a volunteer

01:06:18.420 --> 01:06:20.350
at Meals On Wheels in
Central Maryland is 70?

01:06:20.350 --> 01:06:23.240
And I was like, which is
great for the 70-year-old.

01:06:23.240 --> 01:06:27.096
Y'all need a new strategy
around volunteers, you know?

01:06:27.096 --> 01:06:30.260
And I will bet
you that there are

01:06:30.260 --> 01:06:32.480
people who would totally
deliver a meal every morning

01:06:32.480 --> 01:06:33.355
before going to work.

01:06:33.355 --> 01:06:35.040
They would do it, right?

01:06:35.040 --> 01:06:37.350
But they need a different
way of thinking about how

01:06:37.350 --> 01:06:39.180
people sign up and da, da, da.

01:06:39.180 --> 01:06:42.170
They clearly don't-- they
just don't get it, right?

01:06:42.170 --> 01:06:44.670
I think that there are people
in marketing who would totally

01:06:44.670 --> 01:06:47.060
donate a couple hours
to help them come up

01:06:47.060 --> 01:06:48.875
with a different
volunteer strategy.

01:06:48.875 --> 01:06:50.250
And it's like,
how do we actually

01:06:50.250 --> 01:06:54.130
put those sort of like cases
that are relatively simple,

01:06:54.130 --> 01:06:57.500
but have a huge
impact on people--

01:06:57.500 --> 01:06:59.670
